From: Robert Dawson <rdawson@cs.smu.ca>=0A=
Date: Fri, 18 Nov 2016 15:46:45 -0400=0A=
=0A=
/A minor comment: //=0A=
//The correct plural form of "topos" is "topoi", as the plural form of =0A=
"logos" is "logoi". I vaguely remember that the plural form of "topos" =0A=
was already discussed on this board. //=0A=
/ /=0A=
//In ancient Greek, "(ho) topos" is a noun. Here is a citation: "Ton de =0A=
hyperouranion topon ..." //=0A=
//(Plato, Phaidros, Bibliotheca Oxoniensis, Tomus II, 247 c). This =0A=
citation shows that "topos" is a noun. /=0A=
=0A=
If we were doing category theory in Classical Greek, this argument would =
=0A=
be irrefutable. The claim that it's a noun is, of course, irrefutable =0A=
anyhow.=0A=
=0A=
Embedded in an English sentence, however, "topos" is, a loan word, and =0A=
the pluralization of loan words is inconsistent.  (We also don't decline =
=0A=
them.. or we'd be stuck with topou theory!)=0A=
=0A=
"Duck-billed platypodes," anybody?=0A=
=0A=
Cheers,=0A=
=0A=
Robert=0A=
=0A=
